Communism makes a comeback in Russia.
Moscow — More than a year ago, during a sabbatical from the American university where I was teaching, I returned to my hometown, Moscow.
My destination is not some stronghold of free speech.
But once upon a time, this place still retained some freedom.
Opposition leader Alexei Navalny once traveled across the country in an effort to gain the support of politicians not controlled by the Kremlin.
Popular protests erupted.
Independent non-governmental organizations operate domestically.
Journalists and analysts are not necessarily following the Kremlin's line.
The Communist Party is widely regarded as a relic of history.
Since then, Navalny has been imprisoned, and the protest movement he initiated has been suppressed.
Its anti-corruption foundation was banned for "extremism," and its members are being exiled or investigated.
Almost every day, journalists, media organizations, human rights advocates, or independent institutions are added to the "foreign agent" list — and sometimes even worse — being labeled as "unwelcome individuals."
In the past year, Russia's descent into non-liberal conditions, though not distant, has been very intense.
For example, in 2012, a law was enacted designating foreign agents, with the aim of undermining or discrediting organizations or individuals engaged in "political activities" while simultaneously receiving funding from abroad.
However, the application of this law has become increasingly arbitrary, to the point where even retweeting a tweet can now serve as a reason for being labeled as a foreign agent.
The "unpopular" label can lead to your complete ban.
This year alone, a record 101 entities were added to the list of foreign agents.
The total of 359 includes 88 media-related organizations and individuals.
According to the Russian government, the aforementioned "agents" must be included on the list because they "influence the country's politics."
But of course, the core goal of news and propaganda work is to influence politics.
And this is precisely the problem: although President Vladimir Putin has positioned himself to continue controlling Russian politics in the foreseeable future, he views criticism as a threat to his survival.
Despite enduring all this silence and persecution, it was the Communist Party—an unlikely group—that survived and became the only genuine opposition within the Kremlin.
This is largely due to Navalny's "smart voting" strategy — that is, urging people to support forces most likely to defeat candidates backed by the Kremlin — while the Communist Party performed exceptionally strongly in last month's parliamentary and regional elections.
Official data showed that Communist Party candidates won 18.9% of the votes in the State Duma (parliament), while the United Russia party, supported by the Kremlin, secured nearly 49.8%.
But the communists refused to acknowledge this result, insisting that the vote had been manipulated.
In fact, some experts estimate that they should have received about 30% of the votes, while the United Russia party should have received about 35%.
For many Russians, communists now seem more respected than Putin.
But they are no longer the original communists.
Not only do they not deny the pleasures of the worldly life, but Party members are also seen wearing fur coats, enthusiastic about traveling abroad, driving foreign cars, and using social media.
Some people are millionaires — for example, the charming agricultural director Pavel Grudinin, who was banned from participating in last month's election.
Although the party is still led by Gennady Zyuganov, who is 77 years old, it is increasingly influenced and supported by younger members.
Take Nikolai Bondarenko as an example.
Thirty-six-year-old Bondarenko, nicknamed "Red Navalny," severely criticized the poorly designed pension reform of 2018.
Not long ago, when a regional minister said Russians should be able to "eat better" on a meager monthly salary of 3,500 rubles (about $50), Bondarenko documented his efforts to prove the man wrong on his own YouTube channel.
Despite being threatened with a ban on candidacy, Bondarenko was still allowed to participate in the State Duma elections held last month.
Although he was supported by Navalny's Smart Vote system, he still lost to the candidate from the United Russia party.
But his potential should not be overlooked: he recently drafted a heading for a protest campaign accusing "the state and government" of taking over United Russia.
And then there is Anastasia Yudina, who is 43 years old.
Like Bondarenko, she surprisingly lost the last election.
But she remains very — and increasingly so — popular.
Thanks to the smart voting system, another rising star, elegant Yekaterina Engelicheva, was elected to the Moscow City Duma in 2019.
Ironically, the Communist Party's modernization reflects a longing for the past: in 1917, Lenin's Bolsheviks had promised justice and equality. Though strict, the country that sought to realize these ideals was not devoid of fairness and compassion.
In addition, like the liberal Navalny, today's Communists represent a predictable and consistent vision, under which the whims of an individual do not affect everyone.
It is precisely based on this logic that all of the Kremlin's opponents are increasingly uniting: forming a "United Russia" that can stand against Putin's United Russia Party.
This situation is not limited to Russia alone.
In the recent parliamentary elections in the Czech Republic, Andrej Babiš—also known as the Czech Donald Trump—failed to secure re-election as prime minister, as the opposition coalition set aside their ideological differences and formed a united alliance. The leader of this coalition, Petr Fiala, is likely to lead the new government alongside another opposition alliance.
As Fiala said, "People have had enough of populists," and they want "normal, competent, and decent politics."
The opposition in Hungary will also compile a unified electoral list for the parliamentary elections next year and field a single candidate for the prime minister's post.
Of course, the Czech Republic still maintains a democratic system, and therefore, Babiš is preparing to join the opposition forces.
Overthrowing Putin would be far more difficult, and it is not hard to predict that more comprehensive measures aimed at dismantling the Communist Party will be taken.
However, the above approach also poses risks to the Kremlin.
The current situation is that the president claims Russian democracy "has not died," citing the existence of an "active opposition" as evidence, suggesting that he is at least still interested in maintaining the pretense that Russia has not been driven toward something nearly authoritarian.
Putin said he only wants stability.
But its regime is pushing Russia toward even more turbulent situations.
If the Kremlin were to set and implement rules as capriciously as it has treated the Russian liberals, thereby driving the communists underground, a social explosion would be more likely to occur.
And if it decides to stop repressing, the Russian communists — yes, communists — could become a force that cannot be ignored.
